# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-asia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2002-australian-football-international-cup] The **2002 Australian Football International Cup** was the inaugural international Australian rules football tournament held in Melbourne, Australia in 2002.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2002-australian-football-international-cup] 11 nations participated from around the world and the tournament was officiated by the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2002-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the tournament, finishing undefeated and victorious over Papua New Guinea in the Grand Final on 23 August at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2002-australian-football-international-cup] A 22 player All-International squad was named, however names were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The **2005 Australian Football International Cup** was the second time that the Australian Football International Cup tournament, an international Australian rules football competition was held.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The event was hosted by both Melbourne and Wangaratta, Australia, in 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] 10 nations participated following the late withdrawal of both Nauru and Denmark and the introduction of Spain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] All sides were scheduled to play 4 games, after which the top 4 sides played off in semi-finals for a berth in the Grand Final decider.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was between Papua New Guinea and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Both sides went through the tournament undefeated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] It was played as a curtain raiser to an official Australian Football League premiership season match and was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand were crowned international champions for the first time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The grand final was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The best and fairest medal was awarded to New Zealand's James Bowden.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Like the All-Australian Team in the Australian Football League, a team selected from the best players in the International Cup was selected.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Team members were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The **2011 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup 2011** or **IC11**) was the fourth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 12 and 27 August 2011 by 18 nations, with games played in both Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Two matches were played as curtain raisers to AFL premiership matches, USA vs South Africa at Stadium Australia and the IC Grand Final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won its second men's championship, and the inaugural women's championship (Ryan Aslett Cup).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] 17 of these clubs represented single nations, and one (the Peres Team for Peace) represented both Israel and the Palestinian Territories.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The first round of matches was played with modified rules, most significantly the reduction of game length to two-quarters, in the same manner as the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, the best two teams from each Group were regrouped into four groups of three teams, based on Win-Draw-Loss performance and Percentage in Round 1, all within a larger group known as Division 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would remain in contention for the International Cup title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining six were regrouped in the same way, into two subgroups of Division 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would compete for a secondary prize.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 1 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 2 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups, as well as a single "cross-over" match against a team in the opposite group.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 2, the teams were once again re-seeded based on their performance in the previous round; the teams in Division 1 were seeded in positions 1-12, and the teams in Division 2 in positions 13–18.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These matches were played at the same time as the final round 2 Division 2 matches; the Division 2 teams did not participate in this round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] In the opening round of the Women's International Cup, the five teams played each other once, over the course of 10 days.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, Australia, the lowest ranked team in the competition based on points and percentage, was eliminated and finished in 5th place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining four clubs will compete in the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The **2014 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2014 or **IC14**) was the fifth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between Saturday August 9 to Saturday August 23, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] There are 18 nations competing in the 2014 Tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Of these, 15 competed in the previous tournament; Indonesia and Pakistan make their debuts, while Finland return having previously competed in 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The teams were seeded into three pools of six to decide which teams would play each other, though all teams will be ranked on a single ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The top four teams at the end of Day 3 progress to the International Cup Semi-finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other teams will play another match, depending on their ladder position, with those results added to the Ladder to decide Day 5 matchups.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The 5th to 12th-placed teams will play in Division 1 for the remainder of the tournament, and the 13th-placed team onwards will play in Division 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] For the second consecutive time, there was a concurrent Women's tournament alongside the Men's competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Seven teams participated from five countries - the United States and Canada both fielded two teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Each team played four matches across five matchdays.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Matches played on Saturday 16 August - the "Community Round" of the tournament - were played as curtain-raisers to other amateur Metropolitan and Country football matches to be confirmed; all other games in the round-robin were held at Royal Park, Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] After the round-robin tournament, the last placed team was eliminated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other six teams played one extra match to decide the final placings, with the top two teams on the ladder playing in the Women's International Cup Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The **2017 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2017 or IC17) was the sixth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, a triennial international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 5–19 August 2017, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous men's tournament champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Previous women's winners (Ireland and Canada) also competed in the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea achieved its 3rd men's title and Ireland achieved its 2nd women's title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 AFL International Cup was played in Melbourne from 5 to 19 August, with 18 men's teams and eight women's teams competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The European Crusaders was a combined team made up of women from Britain, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Poland and Sweden.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] In the table below, the numbers in parentheses refer to the team's Unofficial World Rankings by *World Footy News* prior to the competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's fixture was played across two divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Division One played four matches against other teams within the division and were ranked from one to ten, with finals to follow between the top two placed teams on the ladder, the third and fourth placed teams, and so on.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's Division Two competition and the women's competition saw teams split into two pools of four with each team playing matches against the three opponents in their pool before competing in semi-finals and grand finals based on finishing positions within the pool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The women's grand final was played at Etihad Stadium as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 clash between Carlton and Hawthorn.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's grand final was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 match between Collingwood and Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The majority of the matches were played at Royal Park in the Melbourne suburb of Parkville.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The inclusion of a "Community Round" allowed matches to be played as curtain-raisers to local suburban, amateur and country matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally, the International Cup introduced a "School Round" to be played on 9 August, with games played at suburban and country schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Fixtures for the tournament were released by the AFL on 18 July 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In Asia, Australian rules football dates back to 1910 but was only sporadically played until the 1980s after which it has boomed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Clubs have begun in most Asian countries and a governing body for the region, **AFL Asia** was formed in 2008 to coordinate the Asian Championship and promote its affiliated leagues.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] AFL Asia estimates that there are now more than 10,000 Australian Football players across the continent.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There are now several regional leagues including the South China Australian Football League (SCAFL) (2011); South East Asia Australian Football League (SEAAFL) (2013); Guangdong Australian Football League (GDAFL) and North East Asia Australian Football League (NEAAFL) (2014).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The main tournament and cup competition is the annual Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Played every year since 2000 this international tournament is the pinnacle of Asian Australian football calendar.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It currently comprises teams from over a dozen countries contesting for Asia's greatest trophy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It is also emerging as a spectator sport, with professional Australian Football League matches attracting paying audiences, record attendance was set in Japan with 25,000 attending a 1986 exhibition match at Yokohama Stadium.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] China has hosted AFL matches at Jiangwan Stadium since 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The most prominent player born in Asia is Australian Football Hall of Fame member Peter Bell (of South Korea) while the most prominent locally developed player is Michito Sakaki (of Japan).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules is broadcast into Asia on satellite television through the Australia Network.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football in Japan was first introduced in 1910.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] McLean founded the Seisoka Football Club and was successful in introducing it as a sport to four large high schools in Tokyo by having the rules translated into Japanese.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] McLean had hoped to select a national team, however met with a lack of assistance from Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] McLean returned to Australia and Sydney in 1912 and it is not known if the game survived his departure.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] During the wars, matches were played primarily by Australian servicemen in several countries including Indonesia, Malaysia, Japan, Vietnam and South Korea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Before this time, only informal matches had been played in some countries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A rare example involving participants from other countries was the 1941 game held in Port Dickson, British Malaya.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The sport has been organised in Asia since the late 1980s with teams based in Australian expatriate communities and around universities, such as in Tokyo, Japan.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There existed an informal association for various Asian AFL clubs for some time, but on 27 July 2013 a meeting of Asia's presidents was held in Bangkok to discuss the future of footy in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In all, 13 countries / clubs attended and submissions were received from a further four clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] This was the first time representatives of Asian Australian Rules football had ever met with the sole purpose of preparing a road map for Asian footy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] This meeting lead to the formation of AFL Asia, the official Association for Australian Football in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The most recent Asian Champions are the Malaysian Warriors who defeated the Philippine Eagles in Manila, Philippines on 21 October 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The 2018 AFL Asian Championships will be held in Kuala Lumpur on October 13, 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian and New Zealand soldiers have (in the past) played games of Australian rules football in Afghanistan, most notably on ANZAC Day.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Brunei since 1998 when a social match was held, followed by a meeting to establish the Brunei Australian Rules Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Anthony Rodaughan was duly appointed the League's first president.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The domestic competition soon commenced at the Jerudong International School soccer field, with a three-team competition including players from England, Scotland, New Zealand, Canada and Brunei.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Late 1998/99 saw huge changes in the fledgling competition as the country began ending numerous expat contracts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Player numbers were reduced but the league took stock and continued to provide a regular competition for its members.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] 1999 brought the formation of the Brunei Sharks, a composite side representing the league, playing their first match against the Singapore Wombats.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Sharks' first appearance at the Asian Australian Football Championships was in 2000 in Jakarta.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Cambodia by members of the expatriate Australian community in Phnom Penh since around 2000, when a club nicknamed the Cambodia Crocodiles was formed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Crocodiles hosted other teams from around the Asian region for at least one tournament, but then went into recess.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A new club, now known as the Cambodian Kangas, was under formation in 2008, hosting a four-team Indochina Cup in Phnom Penh in November of that year, but this club also did not last beyond their first tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2010, the Cambodian Cobras formed, hosting the Vietnam Swans in Phnom Penh on July 31.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Cambodian Cobras went from strength to strength in 2011, signing a partnership with the Australian Football League club, The West Coast Eagles.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Cobras changed their name to the Cambodian Eagles and participated in their first Asian Champs in the same year.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A number of Cambodian Australians play for the Southern Dragons in the Southern Football League in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Cambodian Eagles went on to win the 2016 ICC where BJ Fitzgerald was named player of the tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football has been played in China since the 1990s, and is currently played by senior clubs in Guangzhou, Shanghai, Tianjin and Beijing, with the Beijing AFL metro league beginning in 2009.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There are also clubs in the special economic development zones of Hong Kong and Macau that play against Chinese teams from Guangzhou and Guangdong in the South China Australian Football league (SCAFL), since 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A representative team of mainly expatriate Australian players has represented China under the names "China Blues" or "China Reds" in competitions such as the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The first representative team composed entirely of Chinese nationals appeared at the 2008 Australian Football International Cup, competing as the *China Red Demons*.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Since 2011 it has been known as *Team China*.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Australian Football League AFL exhibition match in Shanghai in 2010 and a series of AFL Premiership matches was played there from 2017 to 2019, the first outside of Pacific.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The sport began after the independence of Timor-Leste in 1999 due to Australian Defence Force personnel stationed in the country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The East Dili Eels were founded around this time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2001 an organisation named the Timor Lorosa'e Austrálian Futebal Associacao (TILAFA, English: East Timorese Australian Football Association) was formed in Dili and there were plans to send a team to the Arafura Games in Darwin, although this organisation later disappeared.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2007, an exhibition match was played between the ISF (International Stabilisation Force) Tigers from the ADF and the UN Police Warriors (Jumpers borrowed from the NT Team Waratah Warriors).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Both teams had female players and local Timorese players, played at Democracy Field in Dili, which was constructed by the Combat Engineers, this match was the culmination of several Auskick clinics over two months where up to one hundred kids participated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The match raised $10,000 US for the Mary Mackillop Foundation and went to the local, underprivileged people of Timor.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2008 Luke Gosling and Justin Bayard helped start the Timor-Leste Australian Rules Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The club managed to work with the Northern Territory Football League and Australian Volunteers International to get locals playing the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A national team was created in 2008, though not in time to get to the 2008 International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2008, the East Timor Crocodiles team formed, making their debut at the 2008 Bali 9s tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A governing body, AFL Timor-Leste, was created in 2011 to facilitate sending a team to that year's International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] East Timor, playing as *Timor-Leste* participated in its first International Cup in 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The team did participate in 2011 however not win a game and did not return.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Lin Jong, of East Timorese heritage, debuted in 2011 and received a congratulatory letter from Timor Leste Prime Minister Xanana Gusmao.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Jong served as an AFL Multicultural Ambassador and ambassador for the East Timor Hearts Fund.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Hong Kong is home to one of Asia's oldest and most successful Australian rules football clubs, the Hong Kong Dragons having played their first match in 1990.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Based primarily around expat Australians, the club plays frequent matches against other clubs in the Asian region, including other teams from mainland China.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Hong Kong Dragons have won the coveted AFL Asian Championships title six times, in 2003, 2004, 2007, 2012, 2013, 2015.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Hong Kong local teams also play in the South China Australian Football league where they play against teams from southern mainland China and Macau.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Hong Kong also have an active Auskick community with over 400 children participating in Auskick and the HK Junior AFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Spread over 5 centres across Hong Kong teams train weekly and regularly play against other teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The representative team HK Junior Dragons also annually play against the Singapore Sharks and tour Australia playing against Australian local teams and half time at professional AFL games.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Hong Kong Vikings Masters teams born out of Dads from the Junior Auskick centres have been training together in growing numbers and internal Reds v Whites AFL 9's games, social events and once a year play against the Hong Kong Dragons.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In July 1940, a match was played at Kowloon at the Police Club grounds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Known locally as "footy", it is played in India and the country has participated in the International Cup since 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] However India is not currently affiliated to AFL Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] India's national Australian rules team is known as the Tigers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The sport is played in more than 12 Indian states, though it is most popular in the eastern states, particularly Jharkhand and West Bengal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The current record attendance is 20,000 set in 2018 up from 6,000 in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Chakraborty Medal is awarded to the best player from India and is named after Sudip Chakraborty the first member of the Australian Rules Football in India Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The West Australian Football League toured India in 1969, playing two exhibition matches in New Delhi between East Perth and Subiaco Football Clubs, which attracted large crowds and interest, a record 3,500 spectators turned out for one of the matches.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football began in India with the creation of the Indian Amateur Australian Football Association in 2001.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The organisation was based in Delhi, but disbanded in 2004.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The potential for the game has several times attracted interest from Australia, with the WAFL in 2005 proposing an exhibition match for Mumbai.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The next appearance of organised Australian rules in India came with the visit of Brian Dixon to Kolkata in 2006 which resulted in the formation of starter clubs in the city and a platform for the development of an Indian team for the 2008 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The first Indian national team was drawn from players recruited by the AFL India in Kolkata, as well as Indian nationals living in Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2008 Ricky Ponting launched Australian Rules Football in India (ARFAI) in Kolkata after he and Shane Warne had popularised the sport while playing with the Kolkata Knight Riders.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian expatriate Lincoln Harris kickstarted a junior competition in Mumbai in 2010.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A major tournament was promoted in 2012 featuring Steve Waugh as Australian patron.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Richmond Football Club (Tigers) expressed strong interest in holding an AFL exhibition match in India in 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The idea has been furthered by the club in 2012 and 2018, although plans were put on hold during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2017, the Bharat Warriors Football Club were founded in Melbourne with the aim of recruiting players of Indian origin to promote Australian rules football in India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The club operates exchange programs between Australia and India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Despite no AFL matches being staged, a match held in 2017 between the Indian national team and an Australian AFL Masters side attracted over 6,000 spectators at Paschim Medinipur district (West Midnapore).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In April 2018, AFLW player Jess Dal Pos visited Mumbai to conduct young girls clinics in the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2018, 20,000 people attended a national championships match at Similipal Mini Stadium in Bholagoria.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] With play resuming post-COVID-19, Australians have been called in to officiate matches including the AFL India Championships due to a lack of officials in the country to cope with the growth.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2023, India Warriors made a three-peat in the TAC Unity Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football was played in Indonesia by Australian soldiers in 1945 in Morotai and also Ngada.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It is currently played in Indonesia by clubs in Jakarta (formed in 1995), Bali (formed in 1997) and the Borneo Bears based in Balikpapan, these three clubs being mainly made up of expatriate Australians.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There is also a league consisting of local villagers around the Pancawati area in West Java.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Jakarta Bintangs and Bali Geckos regularly contest the Java-Bali Cup and participate in the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A club was under formation as of 2006 in Banda Aceh, although this project was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Founded in 2003, the West Java Australian Football League (WeJAFL) has over 500 local junior and senior players in the local competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The large number of local players makes it the Asian nation with the highest participation rate amongst locals, and the club sent an Indonesian team, the Indonesian Garudas, composed of members of all the Indonesia clubs to the Australian Football International Cup in 2014.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Jakarta Bulldogs Australian Football Club, established in late 2006, is an Aussie Rules Football Club made up of primarily of Under 18 year old expatriate and local students from the British International School Jakarta, although they share no affiliation with the school.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The club was founded by Australian-born brothers Alf Eddy (Club Captain) and Max Eddy (Head Coach) and has played against a wide variety of local Australian Football teams such as the Pancawati Eagles, Depok Garudas, the Bandung-New Guinea AFC and the Jakarta Bintangs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Since 2006 the club has gone from strength to strength obtaining full sponsorship from ANZ Bank which allowed for the acquisition of proper uniforms of AFL standard and new footies in 2007.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2008 Bulldogs will take part in the inaugural Junior Asian Championships, going into the competition with high expectations from all involved.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A Finnish member of the club, Tuomas Anttila, was scouted to play with the Finnish national team at the 2008 International Cup, but was unable to make the journey.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Borneo Bears were formed in Balikpapan in 2008, making their debut at the 2008 Bali 9s tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Indonesia's national team is known as the Garudas.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football in Indonesia receives regular coverage from the Jakarta Globe and is now regularly played on television via the Australia Network including live coverage of the AFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football in Japan is coordinated by the AFL Japan, with a national league based mainly in Tokyo (affiliated with the Australian Football League) but with clubs in Osaka, Nagoya and Hiroshima.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Development teams from the AFL Japan regularly tour to Australia and have competed at all Australian Football International Cups to date.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Lao Elephants were formed in Vientiane in 2007, as the first Australian Rules Football club in Laos.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The team played their first international fixture against the Vietnam Swans and Thailand Tigers in November 2007 in Hanoi.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Lao Elephants impressed many by defeating archrivals Vietnam and Thailand on debut at the Asian Australian Football Championships in Singapore in September 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Later, the "Phants" were victorious in the Mekong Cup held in Phnom Penh, Cambodia on 22 November 2008, involving the Cambodian Kangaroos, Thailand Tigers, Vietnam Swans and Lao Elephants.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The first domestic match in Laos was held in May 2009, with the Northerners (squad members based in Vientiane and Luang Prabang) defeating the Southerners (mine workers from the Sepon area) in Savannakhet.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Macau Lightning AFL club was formed in 2009 and began running Auskick Clinics at the International School of Macau.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] With an increasing demand for more football from the kids participating, the club started Saturday morning training which continues to grow with boys and girls aged between 4 and 13 years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In September 2010 the Macau Lightning Auskick played their first match against the Hong Kong Auskick marking the first of many future match days between both clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It was a small beginning for the Senior Macau Lightning Team in 2009 with only a handful of guys looking for a social kick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] As word spread of AFL in Macau numbers gradually grew to a competitive squad of 30 players by May 2010.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] 2010 has seen the Senior Team make their International Debut with matches against Hong Kong Dragons in May, touring to Guangzhou in August and participating in the China Cup against the Hong Kong Dragons and the China Reds in early September.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] On April 13, 2013, the Lightning achieved their greatest team feat thus far in the short existence defeating both the Hong Kong Blues and a combined Hong Kong team in Round 4 of the SCAFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football is regularly played in Malaysia, currently the main Australian Rules Football team is the Malaysian Warriors who will play four home and four away games in 2015 as well as the Manila Cup tournament and the Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The earliest known history of Australian rules football in Malaysia goes back to the Australian armed forces (2/19th battalion) playing at Port Dickson in 1941.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian servicemen also attempted to introduce the code to Malays at Penang in 1958 and 1963.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Regular games have been played since the late 1980s in Kuala Lumpur, primarily by expatriate Australians living and working in the city.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The club was initially known as the MARK Tigers (Malaysian Australian Rules Kelab) and the team played their first game in February 1993 against Hong Kong in Kuala Lumpur and first toured to Singapore in July 1993.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] They recorded their first win in August 1994 against a team from the Royal Australian Air Force base in Butterworth, Penang.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Between 1994 and 1998, the club became consistent contenders on and off the field in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Games were mainly played against the RAAF in Penang, the Singapore Wombats and the Jakarta Bintangs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Asian economic crisis of 1998 saw many members of the Australian community in Malaysia return home, leaving the club in great difficulties.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2000 the team reformed under a new name, the Malaysian Warriors and have played continually since.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Warriors also participate in an annual five match series of International Rules games against the Orang Éire Gaelic Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The most notable results for the Warriors to date have been the 2012 Manila Cup winners, Premiers of Asia in 2013 and 2015, and runner up in the 2015 Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Warriors train at Padang Merbok, located near the Lake Gardens, Kuala Lumpur.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] More recently ex AFL players Daniel Chick and Tim Fleming have played games for the Warriors, with Fleming scoring 7 goals in a game against Jakarta which Malaysia went on to win to retain the 'Batik Cup'.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Warriors had an unbeaten 2015 season before the Asian Australian Football Championships and finished on top of the AFL Asia ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2016 they contested the Manila Cup and the 2016 Asian Australian Football Championships as well as various home and away games most notably the 2016 Anzac Day clash against the Thailand Tigers in Kanchanaburi.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Mongolian Wolves joined Asian Australian Football Championships in 2019.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The first matches in Nepal were played in 2013 by the *Thyangboche Yaks* and local children also began playing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] More regular matches were later played and the *Himalayan Leopard* club were formed around 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Further growth was facilitated by the Association of Nepalese Alumni from Australia, and Nepal was granted entry to AFL Asia in 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football began in 2014 and has grown rapidly.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It was first introduced by Chaudrey Zulfiqar Ali and Tayyab Chattha with support from the Australian High Commission.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Teams were established in Islamabad, Rawalpindi, Multan and Gujranwala.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The code in Pakistan benefits greatly from access to full sized grounds with cricket there being the most popular sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It is currently strongest in the Swat Valley, where a large competition operates and draws large enthusiastic crowds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] AFL Pakistan (connected with an anti-drug charity network) was formed to govern the sport and select the national team, which has participated in the Australian Football International Cup every tournament since 2014.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A major national tournament was organised in 2018.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australia sent a coach to assist Pakistan in 2019 however the sport's rapid growth in popularity was greatly outpacing local officials ability to support it.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] 10 of Pakistan's more than 15 clubs contested the 2021 AFL Pakistan National Championships in Islamabad.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Islamabad Tigers have been the dominant club with 5 national titles.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Pakistan sent a team to the Asian Championship in 2022, however met some roadblocks to participation due to funding.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Despite challenges sending a team, it won the Division 3 title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2022 AFL Asia reported that Pakistan was the largest and fastest growing nation for the sport in Asia with over 5,000 players with a 45% annual increase in participation.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] From a handful of clubs in 2014, AFL Pakistan grew to over 15 clubs in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Philippine Australian Football League (PAFL) was created in 2004.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Trimmers and Bangers are considered the greatest players in the PAFL.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The league currently runs a two-team competition in Manila.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The teams, the Dingoes and the Eureka's, were originally based on the division of Victorian (Eurekas) and Non-Victorian (Dingoes) players, but with expansion that divide has not been followed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] PAFL hosted the 2005 and 2014 Asian Australian Football Championships, its representative side is known as the Philippine Eagles.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Eagles won their first AFL Asian Championships in 2016 in Vietnam.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football started in Singapore in April 1993, when a group from the Australian expatriate community founded the Singapore Lions (later Wombats) Australian Football Club.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Singapore Wombats play matches throughout each year against visiting Royal Australian Navy ships, as well as a number of tour matches against other expat-based teams from around Asia in the AFL Asia League and the Bali Masters.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] 2007 for Junior and Auskick players and since 2014 Masters/Dads team was added.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Sharks juniors play weekly at the Australian International School (AIS) on Lorong Chuan, Singapore and have toured to Australia, Shanghai, Hong Kong and played at half time of several professional AFL games.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules was played in South Korea during the Korean War.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] On August 29, 1950, Australians stationed on the USS Bataan (CVL-29) introduced it, playing along with locals in front of bemused onlookers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australians and New Zealanders played further matches in 1951.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 1953, VFL matches were broadcast to Australian troops stationed in Korea via radio.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 1954, Australians stationed in South Korea built a dedicated Australian rules football ground and played matches of both football and also used the ground to play cricket against the English.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] South Korean born Peter Bell debuted in the Australian Football League in 1995 and played 286 games and kicked 250 goals during his AFL career in which he was Fremantle Football Club captain, played in 2 AFL Premierships and was two time All-Australian.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] AFL South Korea was formed in 2022 and became a member of AFL Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules was introduced to Sri Lanka in 2016 and the country participated in the 2017 Australian Football International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Interest in Australian rules in Sri Lanka dates back to 1910, with a failed proposal for the Young Australia League to tour Colombo.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A group of AFL officials met with the country's Minister of Internal Trade & Cooperatives, Johnston Fernando in 2010.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Manel Dharmakeerthie and Milton Amarasinghe, a former Director General of Sports, worked together to develop Australian Football in Sri Lanka.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Their first aim is a tournament to be held in 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Fernando was supportive of their plans, and has agreed to offer, "his fullest support to develop footy (in Sri Lanka)." Several current and former AFL players were also present at the meeting, including the AFL's new International Ambassador, Brett Kirk.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The players are in Sri Lanka to learn more about that country's indigenous Vadda people and their place in Sri Lankan society, in an attempt to assist Australia's own indigenous communities upon their return.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Cricketer Ricky Ponting who popularised the sport on the sub continent in 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Sri Lanka affiliated with AFL Asia in 2018 along with Nepal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Thailand since the 1990s with the creation of the Thailand Tigers by Australians living in the city of Bangkok.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Tigers run a domestic social league in Bangkok, as well as competing as the Tigers in regional competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Tigers hosted the 2007 Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Thailand Tigers, was established in the 90's and has grown strong ever since.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The club plays weekly intra-club matches fighting for the inaugural 'Bob & Gerry Cup' (the club founders).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Also playing in international tours including hosting the annual Anzac Day Cup and events such as Indo-China tri-nations and the Asian Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Tigers is now a tradition for expat's from Australia and beyond, extending to the Tigers netball team for the ladies, bringing everyone together regularly for sports and social events.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Family, partners and children are always welcome to Tigers events.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Every year for Anzac Day, the Tigers invite an international club for a special match commemorating the memory of the prisoners-of-war (POW) working on the Hellfire Pass, part of the Burma Railway, during World War II.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The day begins early with both teams attending the dawn service at Hellfire Pass, the moving tribute sets the tone for the day.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The full-time match fielding 14 on field players commences 1:30pm in the full heat of Kanchanaburi close to the Myanmar border.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The match is also attended by the Quiet Lions and VIP guests of the last remaining Diggers (POW's) who attend every year for the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] At the game's end the winning team and best player are presented with their awards by 'Snowy' a tribute to mankind with a genuine Aussie personality.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Anzac Day Cup held in Thailand is open to all public.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football has been played in Timor Leste since the 1990s with the creation of the Timor Leste Crocodile's by Australians living in the city of Dili.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Australian rules football was first played in Vietnam during the Vietnam War.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A match was played in May 1966 between members of the 5th Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 1971, Australian Force Vietnam (AFV) and 110 Signal Squadron played a match in Saigon organised by Private Conboy of Clifton Hill, Victoria a previous member of Melbourne Football Club Under 19s squad.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Lance corporal Ian Granland of 104 Signal Squadron organised a game of Australian Football at Nui Dat in 1970.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There weren't too many grounds of a suitable size on which the game could be played, but luckily it was learned that there was one within the Task Force Area in the area of 1 Australian Reinforcement Unit.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Lance corporal Geoff Morris and Granland did a recce and located the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It was big enough for Australian Football and it even had posts erected but the grass literally ranged from 20 cm to 1m in height.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] That meant that it would have to be cut!
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In the meantime Granland organised a game against 106 Field Workshops.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Word of mouth informed the two that 105 Field Battery had an old Massey Ferguson Tractor with which they used to tow their guns around, plus a slasher.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Permission to use it for mowing the ground was given.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Morris became the driver and the machine was driven over to the field and he began driving it round and round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] He got the grass down reasonably short but certainly not bowling green stuff however good enough.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The mowing had to be done the day before the game because any earlier and the grass would have grown significantly enough to require another cut.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] This was pre centre square and 50m arcs so a hand mower was used for the goal squares, centre circle and boundary.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Lance Corporal Granland umpired the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The players turned up in their Land Rovers and trucks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] What jumpers they wore is till a mystery but it certainly wasn't 'skins v shirts'.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There were players of all ages, size and shape and some bloody good footballers amongst them too.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A photograph of this game would be a gem today.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The umpire copped a bit of abuse from the opposition but that was par for the course.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It was in the days of the one central umpire.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The out of bounds on the full rule had only just been introduced and of course it was applied.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Some of the older heads were not too happy but recognized that it had become a law of the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Many of the blokes who had probably been pretty fair footballers in their youth but now in their late thirties or so they were no match for youth and speed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Some of these tried to slow the youngsters down by wacking them but the umpire was on top of that.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] There was no function after the match or anything, just back to the units.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] But, it was a good relief because obviously everyone who played etc. just loved the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Organised Australian rules football has been played in Vietnam since 1998 when the Saigon Saints, was formed by expatriate Australians.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] It was followed shortly after by new rivals the Hanoi Hawks, also established by Australian expatriates.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Saigon Saints stopped playing in 2001.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2003, footy was reborn in Hanoi under the Hanoi Swans banner with a tri-nations tournament against Hong Kong and Thailand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2007, a movement started in Saigon to get footy up again with the goal of combining with Hanoi to form a national team, the Vietnam Swans.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In July 2007, the Vietnam Swans, played together for the first time in Bangkok for the 8th Annual Asian Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] They returned to the Asian Championships in 2008 in Singapore and have been playing ever since.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2009, highlights included the ANZAC Day Match against the Thailand Tigers at Hellfire Pass on the Death Burma Railway; a Black Saturday Tribute Match and Fundraiser against the Bali Geckos a match against HMAS *Darwin* and the Asian Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A team drawn from the Melbourne Vietnamese community also competed in the Australian Football Multicultural Cup in both years of the competition's existence (2004, 2005) and has competed against touring teams from the Japan Samurai.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Members of this team have expressed interest in working to develop Aussie Rules amongst local players in Vietnam, with plans to visit Hanoi for matches against the Vietnam Swans.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] Players from this squad eventually formed the Elgar Park Dragons, a team mainly made up of Vietnamese-Australians affiliated with Box Hill North in the Victorian Amateur Football Association.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] In 2009, the Dragons became a stand-alone club under the name Southern Dragons, moving to the Southern Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] The Dragons have since moved back to the VAFA.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-asia/australian-rules-football-in-asia] A number of Vietnamese members of the Elgar Park Dragons also played for Team Asia at the 2008 Australian Football International Cup.
